"Here is a feather and here is a stone. Which is heavy and which is light? What a silly question, you say. The stone is heavy and the feather is light, of course!Here is an elephant and here is the same stone. Which is heavy and which is light? What an absurd question, you say. The elephant is heavy and the stone is light, of course!Wait, didn’t you just say that the stone was heavy? Yes, that was because it was heavier than the feather! But it is MUCH lighter than an elephant.So maybe it is best not to say, “This is heavy,” or “This is light.” Maybe it is better to ask: Is this heaviER than something else? Is this lightER than something else?But what about the question  How heavy is this stone? Can we find the answer without talking about elephants or feathers? Yes, we can! We can compare the weight of the stone to something called a kilogram*. A kilogram is used to find out how heavy or light a thing is. A good question to ask then is  How much heavier than a kilogram is the stone? Or How much lighter than a kilogram is our stone? *A ‘kilogram’ is the same thing as ‘kilo’ or ‘kg’. From now on, let’s say kg when we mean kilogram – it’s shorter.But how heavy is a kg? Let's see. You tell the vegetable vendor at the market, “Please give me  kg of onions. "" The vendor puts a kg weight on one side of the scale and piles onions on the other side until the two sides are level. You count the onions on the scale. There are  onions. That tells you that  kg is as heavy as  onions. But this is not entirely reliable. When the onions are small,  kg may be as heavy as  onions. When they are big,  kg may be only as heavy as  onions.We need to find something that weighs EXACTLY  kg. I know! A litre bottle of water weighs exactly  kg. Now that we know this, let’s get back to our elephant. How heavy is an elephant in kgs? Around ,  kg! So if you could get an elephant to sit on one side of a pair of scales, you would need a whopping ,  litre water bottles to balance its weight.,  kg is also the weight of  cows, or  mediumsized dogs.Now that we have talked about some Very Heavy things, let us ask a bolder question  How heavy is the Earth? The Earth, including all the creatures in it, weighs . . .. . . , , , , , , , ,  kgs! Or as much as , , , , , , , ,  litre water bottles! That is very, VERY heavy! Even if we used all the water on earth, there would not be enough to fill them all.Uff. This conversation is getting too heavy. Let us bring the feather back. How light is a feather? It is roughly , ,  times lighter than a kg. If you put a litre water bottle on one side of a scale, you would have to put about , ,  feathers on the other side to make the two sides balance.A raindrop is about ,  times lighter than a kg. Roughly ,  raindrops will weigh as much as a litre bottle of water. A grain of salt is about , , ,  (two crore) times lighter than a kg. That is very, VERY light!Phew! You must be feeling quite lightheaded now. And your brain must be buzzing with questions. Questions like: How do we weigh a grain of sand? How on earth did people weigh the Earth? Who decided the weight of  kg? Bet you can’t wait to find the answers when you grow up!Guesstimate It Perfect for both classroom and home, this activity will help children get a feel for weight estimation. You will need:  A pair of scales with two pans and weights*  A litre bottle filled with water  Objects of different weights found in school or at home  a small bag of vegetables, a book, a duster, a packet of rice, and so on. What to do: . Pass the bottle of water around the class asking each child to feel its weight. This gives them a sense of how heavy a kg is. . Pass the other objects around one by one, asking each child if the object feels heavier or lighter than  kg. Also ask each to guess the actual weight of each object and write it on the board. . Weigh each object on the scales, first against the litre bottle (to answer the question 'Is it heavier or lighter than  kg? ') and then against the actual weights, to see how good each child's guesstimate was. *If it is difficult to find a pair of scales, invite the local vegetable vendor to your classroom (with his scales! ). In Step  above, pass bags of vegetables (of different weights) around.Think About It . On page , you found out that a litre bottle of water weighs exactly  kg. How many water bottles would add up to YOUR weight? . You now know that an averagesized Indian elephant weighs about ,  kgs. If we told you that a train loaded with passengers weighs the same as  elephants, can you find out how many kgs it weighs? . Which is heavier– kg of iron or  kg of cotton wool?Answers: . , ,  (ten lakh) kgs ( x  = , , ) . They are both EQUALLY heavy because both weigh the same– kg! But  kg of cotton wool would take up a LOT more space than  kg of iron."	./Story text files/67.txt	4825	14	5.120622568093385	440	74	225	49.270833333333336	52	44	49	11.333333333333334	37	59	313	201	6	1.1905511811023621	591	44
Batloung village was a dull African village, where nothing interesting had happened before …… until one day, when an unusual child was born. Baby Mogau had a full set of teeth!Local villagers flocked to Mma Mogau’s home to witness this miracle.With his big smile, Mogau brought happiness to the village.Soon, Mogau’s parents realised he was a gifted child. By the time he was six months old, he could walk, read books and paint pictures.Mogau painted the same picture over and over. His mother realised that they needed to find the place in his paintings.They left the village and started their journey. The villagers who loved Mogau’s smile decided to follow them.They travelled for many days, walking through forests, over streamsand past big mountains.Finally, they reached Mogau’s special place. It looked exactly like his paintings!They got to work, setting up a new village – a village where everyone was happy.When Mogau was old enough, he became the king of this colourful village. Mogau’s kingdom of happiness grew and became known, near and far. He was the king who made his people smile!	./Story text files/384.txt	1098	18	6.392857142857143	86	26	139	60.05555555555556	7	11	23	11.0	5	13	71	41	4	1.639344262295082	104	18
